Hi, everybody. My name is Becca Kraus. I'm happy to be here. I work at GSK in our Statistics and

00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:14.880
Data Science Innovation Hub, where my team works on tools and solutions to support our users across

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:20.320
our biostatistics department. And today I'll be talking about one of these tools that we created

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:28.160
called the Slushy R package, which helps our teams build a bridge to the future. So we're no longer

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:35.279
at RStudio Conf anymore. We're at posit Conf. So now more than ever, we have a wide variety of

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:40.880
folks in the rooms with all sorts of different preferences when it comes to software and

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:46.959
different experiences. But if there's something we all know and we all can agree on here, it's that

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
penguins are really cute. And they're not just adorable little creatures, but they're really,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.400
really sophisticated, because they live in these very, very cold, windy conditions, right? And so

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:09.919
their sophistication comes from the fact that they work together to stay warm. And so they do

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:14.959
this technique called Penguin Huddle, where they group in really, really close together,

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:20.720
and it helps them generate heat and conserve energy. And they don't just stand still, they

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:26.720
kind of move around in this coordinated fashion so that everyone has the opportunity to stay nice

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:36.639
and cozy in there. So much like these penguins depend on having a nice, cozy, warm huddle that

00:01:36.639 --> 00:01:43.599
they can rely on, those of us using open source software depend on having safe places to do our

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:51.919
work, right? So in regulated industries, this particularly rings true. So I come from pharma,

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:58.559
that's one of several regulated industries, and we put a lot of care and attention into

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.519
making sure we have stability and consistency when it comes to the software that we're using.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:12.800
So like I said, a lot of care and attention is put into making sure this happens.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:23.039
A common solution for ensuring this is by creating a lockdown centralized environment

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:28.960
where people can come and do their work. These types of environments are sometimes nicknamed

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:34.559
frozen environments because they are, they do not change, they cannot change. A user cannot

00:02:34.559 --> 00:02:41.279
modify them, and they are snapshot to a single point in time. The contents of these environments

00:02:41.279 --> 00:02:48.399
in terms of the R packages that get installed are carefully vetted and assessed and tested

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:57.440
to make sure that they are as accurate, reliable, stable as possible. If any of you attended the

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.000
previous session, there was a pharma track in this room just a little bit ago. My colleague

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:11.520
Ben talked about how we're growing the use of R at GSK. We have a lot of new teams,

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:17.199
teams that are new to R, and these environments have this added benefit of being incredibly

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:24.240
user friendly. They can start learning R without needing to, you know, learn about installing

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.559
packages and managing versions and all sorts of things. It's just available for them. They can log

00:03:28.559 --> 00:03:36.639
in and hit the ground running. Now, with the increased use of R, we start to see a wider

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:41.919
variety of use cases. Different teams have different timelines. They have different needs.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:47.360
On top of that, we have people that are really excited to use new features. And the thing about

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:54.559
the frozen environment is it doesn't change, right? The rest of the open source world moves along

00:03:54.559 --> 00:04:00.399
very, very quickly. And so, these environments get out of date quickly. So, how do we support,

00:04:01.679 --> 00:04:06.399
you know, it starts to look a little bit like, you know, when we're trying to support teams and

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:10.880
figure out things for them, it starts to feel a little bit like my toddler and this toy here

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:20.160
jamming it in. So, how do we support our teams that where the provided solution that's one size

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:24.799
fits all is not quite the right fit for them? You know, what do we tell them to do?

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:34.559
Well, we have another solution that is accessible to all of us, which is the open R world, right?

00:04:34.559 --> 00:04:41.279
Where you install R and you can use whatever packages you like. So, if teams opt for this

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:49.760
solution, they can explore wherever they want. They can make changes and access new things and

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:56.160
they make the rules. But within reason, right? Because these teams are still working on a

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:02.720
collaborative project where there's more than one person and they're coming up against deadlines a

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:11.760
lot of the times. So, they generally need to try to stay in the same area. So, luckily for us, we

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:18.399
have an incredible tool at our fingertips developed by Posit, which is the RM package.

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:28.480
So, RM is a great way for people to begin to huddle up and get in the same area in terms of

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:33.359
what types of software they're using. So, that they can begin to have something that's more

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:43.040
reproducible. Our teams, they need a little bit more guidance when it comes to, you know,

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:47.600
where are they forming their huddle? What are they forming their huddle around? How closely

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:53.600
together do they need to be? What if they need to go off and get food and come back later,

00:05:53.600 --> 00:06:04.160
like these penguins do? So, this is why we created Slushy. Slushy is an R package that is

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:10.799
designed to support our teams that want to use an open R environment and need to figure out how to

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:18.720
huddle up effectively and efficiently. Our Slushy, we originally created it internally and we decided

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:25.359
to open source the code to share it with the community. So, I'll share the GitHub link at the

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:33.920
end. But Slushy makes use of a couple of really awesome existing tools. I mentioned RM already.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:42.559
And it also makes use of another tool developed by Posit, which is Posit Package Manager.

00:06:43.119 --> 00:06:50.079
On top of these two things, it gets us, or these two things alone, get our teams a long way.

00:06:51.119 --> 00:06:58.559
But they still need some additional supports. And so, in addition to these two things, we have

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:07.279
some, we're adding some additional functionality to help guide our users through their journey,

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:12.880
so it's nice and smooth. We're also putting in some guardrails for them,

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:17.679
so they can stay on track better and make sure everything's nice and easy for them

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:23.040
as they're adapting to this ever-changing open source landscape, right?

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:33.519
So, we had a few goals when it came to building Slushy. And one of those was to help people

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:43.839
find a home where they could begin to feel warm and cozy and have the confidence to hit their

00:07:43.839 --> 00:07:50.239
ground running with building their, doing their coding just like they do in a frozen environment.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:08:01.679
So, first and foremost, the RM package is absolutely fundamental in helping our users

00:08:01.679 --> 00:08:07.600
begin to form that huddle, begin to form that home base. If you're not super familiar with RM,

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:14.559
what it does is, well, it does a lot of awesome things, but one of its key features is helping

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:20.239
everyone on the same team use the same packages. And not just the same packages, but the same

00:08:20.239 --> 00:08:25.440
versions of those packages, so that code that I write will work for you and vice versa.

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:32.320
Now that we have a way to begin to huddle up, we need to help our teams figure out what to huddle

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:39.359
around. They're looking to us to give them guidance about, you know, what packages do I use?

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:46.080
So, if we think back to our frozen environments, those centralized environments and all of that

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:54.159
vetting that happens to decide what packages go in there, that vetting results in a subset of

00:08:55.039 --> 00:09:03.359
packages that are deemed to be accurate and reliable. If that decision has been made on

00:09:03.359 --> 00:09:09.599
an organizational level or department level, we can leverage that and get those packages into those,

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:16.479
in to be used by that team, and that is their agreed upon set of packages. They can also do

00:09:16.479 --> 00:09:22.960
that legwork themselves. In either case, a vetting step will lead to this subset of packages that the

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:29.520
team aligns on, and it will help to kick off that huddle. Also, through that vetting process,

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:35.919
we can be sure that each one of these packages is going to work well individually. But with all

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:42.000
of the moving parts in open source, we want to also be sure that all these packages will be

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.679
compatible with one another. In our case, most of our packages are coming from CRAN.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:57.200
So, when a package gets released to CRAN, all of its checks and tests get run automatically,

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:02.880
and because everything on CRAN is so interconnected, there's also, as a byproduct,

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:08.880
any other package that's connected into that package some way is checked for consistency

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:16.239
and compatibility. So, for, you know, everything that's up to date on CRAN as of today is compatible

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:26.000
together. Posit Package Manager is a way for us to access different points in time through what's

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:32.479
called snapshots. These CRAN snapshots are dated, as you can see from the calendar, and we can hook

00:10:32.479 --> 00:10:37.679
into any one of these snapshots and get access to the CRAN ecosystem and have confidence that

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:43.520
everything is going to work well together. Something else I want to point out here is,

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:50.320
with a lot of our newer R users, this is a big boost in their learning journey because

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:54.239
thinking about all the individual packages and their different versions

00:10:54.960 --> 00:11:00.479
is a little bit overwhelming, right? And so, when we shift to the snapshot mindset,

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:05.359
it really simplifies things for them, and all they have to think about is a date,

00:11:05.359 --> 00:11:08.880
and communicating together is a lot easier around that.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:14.400
So, with these pieces, we have a way to huddle up. We know what we're huddling around, and we can

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:19.039
be sure that, or our teams can be sure that everything they're using is going to work well

00:11:20.159 --> 00:11:27.840
together and individually. And we can get that. So, through Slushy, we have functionality to just

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:35.039
get that huddle into place for the team through the Slushy function, which calls our under the hood.

00:11:35.039 --> 00:11:41.280
Now, we're still, our teams are still working in the open R environment as part of this paradigm,

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:46.799
right? So, we're not blocking access to things. They still have access to really anything they

00:11:46.799 --> 00:11:55.119
want out there. And it can be easy and tempting for people to try new things and veer off course

00:11:55.119 --> 00:12:01.760
a little bit. These teams using Slushy really want to keep everyone nice and tight, and they

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:08.239
really want to keep everyone nice and tight together, and not veer off course, right? We've

00:12:08.239 --> 00:12:14.719
agreed upon a set of packages. We want to stick to those. So, it was important for us to, as part of

00:12:14.719 --> 00:12:21.440
Slushy, to get some functionality in place to make sure that we are constantly monitoring what the

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.479
teams are using. And so, RM does a great job at this as well, and we're just kind of augmenting

00:12:26.479 --> 00:12:32.239
it to make sure that people are sticking to the packages they intended to use, as well as the

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:38.320
snapshot that they intended to use. So, it really makes sure that no one is lost along the way.

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:47.039
But sometimes, teams need to move around a little bit. You know, after all, huddles are dynamic.

00:12:47.039 --> 00:12:54.799
They are responsive to changes in the environment. And projects can be long, and people can change

00:12:54.799 --> 00:13:00.960
their minds about things. So, one example of somewhere people might want to change

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:08.880
things a little bit is through the agreed-upon set of packages. So, let's say a team a couple

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:14.159
months down the line finds a really great package. They've vetted it. They feel really good about

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:19.760
using it. Through Slushy, we've given them the ability to make sure that that package can get

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:27.760
added in to their environment through this function here, Slushy add. And by adding it in

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:33.440
officially, it makes sure that that package is okay to use. It's no longer going to get flagged

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:38.960
by that previous monitoring step, and they're able to expand things a little bit.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:47.280
Another place people might want to move is through time. They commonly do. They've started

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:52.159
at a snapshot, and, you know, a month later, two months later, things are moving ahead. They want

00:13:52.159 --> 00:13:57.440
access to new features, understandably. So, we want to give them the ability, or we've given

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:05.760
them the ability, to shift things up ahead. In some cases, they might need to also go backwards

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:11.520
if something gets deprecated, or maybe it's a little too risky to make that leap, and they

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:19.280
want to go back. Either way, we've made it just as easy to go forward as it is back

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:26.640
through the Slushy update function. People can optionally pass a date. So, you know, getting

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:32.239
from snapshot to snapshot very specifically, you would pass a date to this function. Otherwise,

00:14:32.239 --> 00:14:38.080
it's just going to bring everything up to date. This function also makes sure that everything in

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:42.880
that library is going to the new snapshot, and no dependencies get left behind or anything like

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:54.799
that, or left ahead if they're going backwards. So, making the leap from snapshot to snapshot

00:14:54.799 --> 00:14:59.599
can be a little bit intimidating. Sometimes it's risky. People might be on really tight timelines.

00:14:59.599 --> 00:15:06.559
So, we want to give them a peek ahead here. So, what we did with Slushy is add in this preview

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:11.440
function that they can call before they actually update all their packages or revert all their

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:17.599
packages. So, this feature allows them to get a peek ahead at what is going to change should they

00:15:17.599 --> 00:15:25.200
make that leap, and they can make plans accordingly. They can begin to do their research and anticipate

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.719
how their code might be impacted by this change, and this really helps us support them through,

00:15:33.359 --> 00:15:38.000
you know, as they move around and make that process smoother.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:47.280
So, it's a lot of different pieces, and we think back to our huddles. Penguins don't read a manual

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:51.599
on how to huddle. They just know how to do it from the time they're little babies, and we want the

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:58.159
same experience for our users. We want them to have success and feel like it's easy to get there,

00:15:58.159 --> 00:16:02.960
and feel like they can just focus on their jobs, get their programming done,

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:05.840
enjoy the process of learning R.

00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:14.320
So, one way to simplify things for them is, of course, by creating an R package,

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:20.080
and we try to be really intentional about, you know, what is the minimum number of steps that

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:25.840
our team needs to make and try to really simplify the functionality to reduce the burden on them

00:16:26.799 --> 00:16:29.280
so they don't have to think too much about all this stuff.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:36.640
Another way we try to simplify things is through our training and recommendations about how to use

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:45.919
Slushy. So, for instance, instead of allowing or recommending everyone on the team can adjust the

00:16:45.919 --> 00:16:54.400
environment, we assign that to one or two individuals who are responsible for initializing

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:59.840
and maintaining the environment, and everyone else just follows suit, and they don't have to

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:06.880
think too much. They just have their library in place, and they can start using it. This decreases

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:14.160
the amount of, you know, the learning curve, of course, and the burden on the teams, but it also

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:21.920
is going to decrease the risk that that environment might change in some way by somebody who's just

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:32.000
trying something out. Another way we've tried to simplify is by creating a config file that kind of

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:39.520
wraps up all of our settings, and Slushy will read that automatically. So, what this allows,

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:46.079
by putting a bunch of settings in a config file, an organization or a team can make

00:17:46.079 --> 00:17:54.560
a standard config file that they can apply to all of their projects. So, this, you know, taking all

00:17:54.560 --> 00:17:59.839
of these settings out of Slushy, the teams don't need to be concerned about it. We've done that for

00:17:59.839 --> 00:18:06.959
them, and through this config file, people can, or we can customize things like the package manager

00:18:06.959 --> 00:18:13.839
URL, whether or not they should be using a cache, whether there's a cache available, that really

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:20.319
makes it faster for the teams to get all of their packages in place, since everyone is installing

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:27.680
the same things one after another. They can do all sorts of RM customizations in terms of

00:18:28.479 --> 00:18:36.079
those settings, special code that should be run before and after Slushy is initialized

00:18:36.640 --> 00:18:42.959
at the start of each session, and perhaps most importantly is the list of approved packages

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:46.800
that should be used from project to project, or the list of agreed upon packages.

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:52.560
So, again, teams don't need to ask that question of what packages should I use? We can just kind of

00:18:52.560 --> 00:19:00.640
get that information to them, or they can make that source of truth themselves and have that standardized.

00:19:00.719 --> 00:19:09.920
So, all of this, Slushy package has really been great to give a predefined kind of off-the-shelf

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:16.640
huddle for our teams to take and use and make their own, which, again, is really excellent,

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:24.640
especially for our newer teams. And another place Slushy has been a big support is for our

00:19:25.199 --> 00:19:36.560
teams who are looking way out into the future for their deadlines. So, again, back to the frozen

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:44.640
environments, they take a lot of effort and time and resource to create because of all the care

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:49.920
that's put into them. So, the cadence at which they're released is spread out a little bit.

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:57.680
So, a team that's looking way out into the future has the opportunity to use a future frozen

00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:04.640
environment when it's available instead of kind of settling for something older right now. And this

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:12.640
will allow them to have some access to the newer features. So, what they can do in the meantime is

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:18.479
set up Slushy, work with the team using or creating the frozen environment to understand, you know,

00:20:18.959 --> 00:20:26.400
what packages are expected to be in there, get those into place for themselves, and update along

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:34.079
the way. And they can fix on the snapshot, and it's kind of smooth sailing to the end.

00:20:34.959 --> 00:20:40.479
This is not just great for our study teams who are empowered to do this on their own. It's great

00:20:40.479 --> 00:20:46.719
for our tech teams who can focus on the task at hand, and both teams can move along in parallel

00:20:46.719 --> 00:20:54.479
towards a common future. So, with that, Slushy has allowed us to build spaces where our users

00:20:54.479 --> 00:20:58.800
can thrive, just like these penguins and their huddle. If you want to learn more about Slushy,

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:08.640
I'm happy to talk at the break where you can visit our GitHub site. So, thank you.

